5","1204":"1204","1148":"1148","1169":"1169","1202":"1202","1178":"1178","about 1205":"about 1205","1232":"1232","Bilbrough, Selby District, North Yorkshire, England":"Bilbrough, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Walton, Yorkshire, England":"Walton, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire East Riding, England":"Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom","Askham Manor, Yorkshire, England":"Manor, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fairfax","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname for someone with beautiful long hair, from Middle English <i>fair fax</i> ‘beautiful tresses’. This was a common descriptive phrase in Middle English: the alliterative poem <i>Sir Gawain and the Green Knight</i> refers to ‘fair fanning fax’ encircling the shoulders of the doughty warrior.","History: Thomas Fairfax (1693–1781), an army officer from Leeds Castle, Kent, England, first came to VA in 1735 and settled on maternal estates there as a proprietor in 1747."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Fairfax was born in 1170, in Manor, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Fairfax, was 20 and his mother, Eustachia Carthrope, was 23. He married Alice de Bugthorpe in 1204, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1249, in his hometown, at the age of 79, and was buried in Bilbrough, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1170–1249":"1170–1249","1172–1195":"1172–1195","1178–1250":"1178–1250","1202–1250":"1202–1250","1150–1205":"1150–1205","1148–1232":"1148–1232","1250":"1250","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1172":"1172","1170":"1170","5 December 1202":"5. detsember 1202","1249":"1249","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1148":"1148","1169":"1169","1202":"1202","1178":"1178","about 1205":"umbes 1205","1232":"1232","Bilbrough, Selby District, North Yorkshire, England":"Bilbrough, North Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Walton, Yorkshire, England":"Walton, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire East Riding, England":"Yorkshire East Riding, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Askham Manor, Yorkshire, England":"Manor, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1170–1249":"1170–1249","1172–1195":"1172–1195","1178–1250":"1178–1250","1202–1250":"1202–1250","1150–1205":"1150–1205","1148–1232":"1148–1232","1250":"1250","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1172":"1172","1170":"1170","5 December 1202":"5. joulukuuta 1202","1249":"1249","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1148":"1148","1169":"1169","1202":"1202","1178":"1178","about 1205":"noin 1205","1232":"1232","Bilbrough, Selby District, North Yorkshire, England":"Bilbrough, North Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Walton, Yorkshire, England":"Walton, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire East Riding, England":"Yorkshire East Riding, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Askham Manor, Yorkshire, England":"Manor, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"